definition.value: A choline that is the parent compound of the cholines class, consisting of ethanolamine having three methyl substituents attached to the amino function.
A sulfur-containing amino acid that is propanoic acid with an amino group at position 2 and a sulfanyl group at position 3.
A simple monocarboxylic acid containing two carbons.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, preservative.
An oxygen hydride consisting of an oxygen atom that is covalently bonded to two hydrogen atoms.
The (R)- enantiomer of camphor.
A carvone having (S) configuration.
A p-menthan-3-ol which has (1R,2S,5R)-stereochemistry. It is the most common naturally occurring enantiomer.

A limonene monoterpenoid consists of a cyclohexene ring substituted by a hydroxymethyl  and a prop-1-en-2-yl group at positions 1 and 4 respectively. It is a constituent of a variety of essential oils including lavender.
The simplest (and the only achiral) proteinogenic amino acid, with a hydrogen atom as its side chain.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): flavour enhancer.
The (+)-enantiomer of catechin and a polyphenolic antioxidant plant metabolite.
A formyltetrahydrofolic acid in which the formyl group is located at position 5.
A member of the class of pterocarpans carrying three hydroxy substituents at positions 3, 6a and 9.
A tetraric acid that is butanedioic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 3.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, antioxidant synergist, sequestrant.
Aldehydic parent sugars (polyhydroxy aldehydes H[CH(OH)]nC(=O)H, n >= 2) and their intramolecular hemiacetals.
Any alpha-amino acid having L-configuration at the alpha-carbon.
A hydroxyisoflavanone that is the 2,3-dihydro derivative of biochanin A.

A primary alcohol is a compound in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom which has either three hydrogen atoms attached to it or only one other carbon atom and two hydrogen atoms attached to it.

An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid resulting from the formal oxidation of each of the terminal methyl groups of butane to the corresponding carboxy group. It is an intermediate metabolite in the citric acid cycle.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator.
A straight-chain, sixteen-carbon, saturated long-chain fatty acid.
A primary amino compound obtained by formal decarboxylation of the amino acid tyrosine.

A hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone that is 1,4-naphthoquinone in which the hydrogen at position 5 has been replaced by a hydroxy group. A plant-derived 1,4-naphthoquinone with confirmed antibacterial and antitumor activities.
A peptide containing ten or more amino acid residues.
A long-chain fatty acid that is a C20, polyunsaturated fatty acid having four (Z)-double bonds at positions 5, 8, 11 and 14.

A tetrahydroxyflavone in which the four hydroxy groups are located at positions 3', 4', 5 and 7. It is thought to play an important role in the human body as an antioxidant, a free radical scavenger, an anti-inflammatory agent and an immune system modulator as well as being active against several cancers.
Any 3-hydroxy steroid whose skeleton is closely related to cholestan-3-ol (additional carbon atoms may be present in the side chain).

An amino sulfonic acid that is the 2-amino derivative of ethanesulfonic acid. It is a naturally occurring amino acid derived from  methionine and cysteine metabolism. An abundant component of fish- and meat-based foods, it has been used as an oral supplement in the treatment of disorders such as cystic fibrosis and hypertension.
A fatty acid with a chain length ranging from C13 to C22.
A  triterpenoid saponin that is the  glucosiduronide derivative of 3beta-hydroxy-11-oxoolean-12-en-30-oic acid.
A pyridinemonocarboxylic acid that is pyridine in which the hydrogen at position 3 is replaced by a carboxy group.
An acyclic carotene commonly obtained from tomatoes and other red fruits.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): colour.

An organic heterobicyclic compound that consists of 2-oxohexahydro-1H-thieno[3,4-d]imidazole having a valeric acid substituent attached to the tetrahydrothiophene ring. The parent of the class of biotins.
A mannose with D-configuration.
A class of glycerophospholipids in which a phosphatidyl group is esterified to the hydroxy group of ethanolamine.
A monocarboxylic acid that is propionic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 3 is substituted by a 2-hydroxyphenyl group.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of trans-caffeic acid with the 3-hydroxy group of quinic acid. It is an intermediate metabolite in the biosynthesis of lignin.
A cholestanoid consisting of cholestane having a double bond at the 5,6-position as well as a 3beta-hydroxy group.

A cyclohexenecarboxylic acid that is cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3, 4 and 5 (the 3R,4S,5R stereoisomer). It is an intermediate metabolite in plants and microorganisms.
A  benzenetriol carrying hydroxy groups at positions 1, 2 and 3.
An octadec-9-enoic acid in which the double bond at C-9 has Z (cis) stereochemistry.
A carbonyl group with two C-bound amine groups. The commercially available fertilizer has an analysis of 46-0-0 (N-P2O5-K2O).
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): flour treatment agent.
A benzenetriol with hydroxy groups at position 1, 3 and 5.
A primary alcohol that is ethane in which one of the hydrogens is substituted by a hydroxy group.
A pentahydroxyflavone having the five hydroxy groups placed at the 3-, 3'-, 4'-, 5- and 7-positions. It is one of the most abundant flavonoids in edible vegetables, fruit and wine.
A lipid containing phosphoric acid as a mono- or di-ester. The term encompasses phosphatidic acids and phosphoglycerides.
An aminoglycan consisting of beta-(1->4)-linked D-glucosamine residues.
Any member of the class of menaquinones that is 2-methyl-1,4-naphthoquinone with an unsaturated isoprenoid chain at the 3-position.
